metadata.title: Cessna 150
aws::graph::propositions: The 707's outer right wing was damaged in a collision with a Cessna aircraft.
The 707 landed safely at Los Angeles International Airport (LAX).
None of the 707's 87 passengers were injured.
None of the 707's 9 crew members were injured.
According to the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB), the cause of the collision was the minimum opportunity for the flight crews to see and avoid the other aircraft.
Background lights behind the Cessna reduced visibility of the Cessna.
The Cessna pilots' visual field was decreased by the aircraft's wing while turning.
On 9 January 1975, Cessna 150H with registration number N50430 collided with a United States Air Force Convair VT-29D.
The collision between Cessna 150H N50430 and the Convair VT-29D occurred at night.
The collision between Cessna 150H N50430 and the Convair VT-29D occurred over the James River off Newport News, Virginia.
The Convair VT-29D was on an instrument landing system approach to Langley Air Force Base when the collision occurred.
The collision killed all people aboard both aircraft.
The pilot of Cessna 150H N50430 was killed in the collision.
The passenger of Cessna 150H N50430 was killed in the collision.
Five crew members of the Convair VT-29D were killed in the collision.
Two passengers of the Convair VT-29D were killed in the collision.

text:
The 707's outer right wing was damaged, but the aircraft landed safely at LAX, and none of its 87 passengers and 9 crew were injured. According to the NTSB, the cause was "the minimum opportunity for the flightcrews [sic] to see and avoid the other aircraft due to the background lights behind the Cessna and the decrease in the Cessna pilots' visual field resulting from the aircraft's wing while turning".
9 January 1975: 150H N50430 collided with a United States Air Force Convair VT-29D at night over the James River off Newport News, Virginia, while the Convair was on an instrument landing system approach to Langley Air Force Base. The collision killed all aboard both aircraft: the Cessna's pilot and passenger and the Convair's five crew and two passengers.
